Triactines and tetractines have cylindrical actines with sharp tips. The apical actine of the tetractines (
Fig. 29D
) is much thinner than the others (resembling that of 

C. contorta

); it is cylindrical, straight and smooth, and frequently shorter. Tetractines can be seen primarily near the pseudoatrium.

There is also another kind of spicule in this specimen that was not described by Schmidt, the trichoxea (
Fig. 29G
). These spicules are very thin, similar to filaments and they are present among the tubes.
